==Development==
[[File:Vice President Joe Biden jokes with Julia Louis-Dreyfus.jpg|thumb|Louis-Dreyfus with then-Vice President [[Joe Biden]] at the White House]]

===''The Thick of It''===

====BBC series====
Before creating ''Veep'', British satirist [[Armando Iannucci]] created the [[BBC]] sitcom ''[[The Thick of It]]'', set in a fictional department of the [[Government of the United Kingdom|British government]]. ''The Thick of It'' was first broadcast in 2005 and won a number of awards. Iannucci directed a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] film, ''[[In the Loop (film)|In the Loop]]'', which was released in 2009 and nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay]].

====ABC pilot====
A pilot for an American version of ''The Thick of It'' was produced as a candidate for the 2007–08 season on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]. Also titled ''The Thick of It'', it was developed for American audiences by writers [[Mitch Hurwitz]] and [[Richard Day (writer)|Richard Day]] and followed a low-level member of the [[United States Congress]] and his staff. Iannucci had a production credit on the show, but he was not otherwise involved. The pilot was produced by [[Sony Pictures Television]] and [[BBC Worldwide]] and directed by [[Christopher Guest]].<ref name="Zap2it0226">{{cite web |url=http://www.zap2it.com/blogs/zap-christopherguestdirectingthethickofit |title=Christopher Guest Jumps Into 'The Thick of It' |publisher=[[Zap2it]] |date=February 26, 2007|access-date=March 16, 2007}}</ref>

In the pilot, [[John Michael Higgins]] played newly-elected Congressman Albert Alger, and [[Oliver Platt]] played committee chairman Malcolm Tucker.<ref name="Zap2it0309">{{cite web |url=http://www.zap2it.com/blogs/zap-pilotcasting-oliverplattchrislowell |title=Platt, 'Piz' Pluck Pilot Parts |date=March 9, 2007 |access-date=March 16, 2007 |publisher=Zap2it}}</ref> [[Rhea Seehorn]] portrayed Ollie Tadzio, an ambitious young speechwriter, and [[Michael McKean]] played Glen Glahm, "a former campaign operative who's now the Chief of Staff" for the congressman.<ref name="Zap2it0315">{{cite web |url=http://www.zap2it.com/blogs/zap-gilmoregirlsmelissamccarthyjoinsabcpilot |title='Gilmore' Regular Joins ABC Pilot |date=March 15, 2007 |access-date=March 16, 2007 |publisher=Zap2it}}</ref>

ABC did not pick up the show for its fall 2007 schedule.<ref name="SFChron070521">{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Sometimes-buzz-about-TV-pilots-is-just-a-lot-of-2593112.php |title=Sometimes buzz about TV pilots is just a lot of hot air |access-date=May 27, 2007 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |first=Tim |last=Goodman |date=May 21, 2007 |archive-date=October 20, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121020163524/http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Sometimes-buzz-about-TV-pilots-is-just-a-lot-of-2593112.php |url-status=live }}</ref> Iannucci distanced himself from the pilot, stating, "It was terrible...they took the idea and chucked out all the style. It was all conventionally shot and there was no improvisation or swearing. It didn't get picked up, thank God."<ref name="HBO">{{cite news|last=Rosser|first=Michael|url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/multi-platform/news/iannacci-in-talks-with-hbo-over-us-thick-of-it/2021907.article|title=Iannacci in talks with HBO over US Thick of It|work=[[Broadcast (magazine)|Broadcast]]|date=April 24, 2009|access-date=April 24, 2009|archive-date=July 3, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090703051430/http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/multi-platform/news/iannacci-in-talks-with-hbo-over-us-thick-of-it/2021907.article|url-status=live}}</ref>

===HBO development of ''Veep''===
After ''The Thick of It'' was dropped by ABC, several networks including [[HBO]], [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] and [[NBC]] expressed interest in adapting the show.<ref name="Yahoo070604">{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2007/06/04/us-thick-idUSN0441749720070604 |title=Rejected by ABC, political satire sparks interest |date=June 4, 2007 |access-date=June 4, 2007 |publisher=Reuters |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |archive-date=January 1, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130101003252/http://www.reuters.com/article/2007/06/04/us-thick-idUSN0441749720070604 |url-status=live }}</ref> Iannucci re-entered talks with HBO (his initial preference) about adapting the series, with the result that a new pilot episode for a series situated in the office of the [[Vice President of the United States]] called ''Veep'' (a nickname derived from the position's initials "VP") was commissioned in late 2009.<ref name="HBO" /> Iannucci was given much more creative control over the production,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2012/04/armando-ianucci-hbos-veep.html |title=Armando Iannucci talks political satire and new HBO series 'Veep' |work=Los Angeles Times |date=April 20, 2012 |access-date=May 11, 2016 |archive-date=June 4, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604144049/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2012/04/armando-ianucci-hbos-veep.html |url-status=live }}</ref> and co-wrote the pilot with British comedy writer [[Simon Blackwell]], who also contributed to the British series ''[[The Thick of It]]''.<ref name="OrderedToSeries"/>

In April 2011, HBO announced that it had ordered ''Veep'' as a series,<ref name="OrderedToSeries">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2011/04/its-official-hbo-announces-series-order-for-comedy-veep-with-julia-louis-dreyfus-123657/ |title=It's Official: HBO Announces Series Order For Comedy ''Veep'' With Julia Louis-Dreyfus |website=Deadline Hollywood |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=April 18, 2011 |access-date=April 21, 2015 |archive-date=April 26, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426230529/http://deadline.com/2011/04/its-official-hbo-announces-series-order-for-comedy-veep-with-julia-louis-dreyfus-123657/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and later announced in January 2012 that the series would premiere on April 22, 2012.<ref name="PremiereDateAnnounced">{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/01/hbo-sets-premiere-dates-for-series-veep-movie-game-change/ |title=UPDATE: Premiere Dates For HBO's 'Girls,' 'Game Of Thrones', 'Veep' & 'Game Change' |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=January 13, 2012 |access-date=April 24, 2012 |archive-date=April 18, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418232234/http://www.deadline.com/2012/01/hbo-sets-premiere-dates-for-series-veep-movie-game-change/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Louis-Dreyfus described ''Veep'''s intent not to have the President on-screen, or to reveal the political party of the characters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cc.com/video-clips/gblljb/the-daily-show-with-jon-stewart-julia-louis-dreyfus |publisher=Comedy Central |title=Julia Louis-Dreyfus |date=April 17, 2012 |access-date=April 21, 2015 |archive-date=September 30, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930151123/http://www.cc.com/video-clips/gblljb/the-daily-show-with-jon-stewart-julia-louis-dreyfus |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/veep-a-playful-pander-in-washingtons-zoo/2012/04/19/gIQAqc0HTT_story.html|title='Veep': A playful pander in Washington's zoo|last=Stuever|first=Hank|date=April 19, 2012|work=The Washington Post|access-date=April 14, 2015|archive-date=April 14, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414103652/http://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/veep-a-playful-pander-in-washingtons-zoo/2012/04/19/gIQAqc0HTT_story.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

==Production==
Directors for Season 1 included [[Armando Iannucci]], [[Tristram Shapeero]] and [[Chris Morris (satirist)|Chris Morris]]. ''Veep'' is executive produced by Iannucci, Christopher Godsick and [[Frank Rich]]. Co-executive producers are [[Simon Blackwell]], [[Tony Roche (writer)|Tony Roche]], with [[Julia Louis-Dreyfus]] and Stephanie Laing as producers. The series' first four seasons featured an entirely British writing staff, including Iannucci, Blackwell, Roche, [[Sean Gray]], [[Will Smith (comedian)|Will Smith]], [[Roger Drew]], [[Ian Martin (writer)|Ian Martin]], [[Andy Riley]], [[Kevin Cecil]], [[David Quantick]], Georgia Pritchett and [[Jesse Armstrong]], among others,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afro.com/sections/arts_entertainment/story.htm?storyid=72668 |title=HBO Begins Filming of 'VEEP' in Maryland |publisher=Afro.com |date=October 5, 2011 |access-date=March 22, 2013 |archive-date=February 3, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203045750/http://www.afro.com/sections/arts_entertainment/story.htm?storyid=72668 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2012/03/26/expletives-not-deleted |title=Expletives Not Deleted |work=The New Yorker |first=Ian |last=Parker |date=March 26, 2012 |access-date=April 21, 2015 |archive-date=April 8, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150408143052/http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2012/03/26/expletives-not-deleted |url-status=live }}</ref> many of whom had previously worked with Iannucci on ''The Thick of It''.

Series creator Armando Iannucci departed as [[showrunner]] following the fourth season's end of production. Iannucci stated that his continuing busy schedule, as well as the challenge of maintaining his family life while switching between [[Baltimore]] and London, would not allow him to "[dedicate] one hundred percent" as head of the show, and he had chosen to "fire" himself as a result. [[David Mandel]] took over as showrunner for future episodes, becoming ''Veep'''s first American writer. Mandel retained a small number of Ianucci's writing staff, as well as [[Chris Addison]] as director and supervising producer, whilst also bringing in his own staff, and American writers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/veep-creator-armando-iannucci-depart-787794 |title='Veep' Creator Armando Iannucci to Depart After Four Seasons (Exclusive) |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Kate |last=Stanhope |date=April 10, 2015 |access-date=April 11, 2015 |archive-date=April 12, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412221037/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/veep-creator-armando-iannucci-depart-787794 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="ibtveep">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/veep-creator-armando-iannucci-explains-why-hes-still-leaving-show-season-5-after-best-2106324|title='Veep' Creator Armando Iannucci Explains Why He's Still Leaving The Show Before Season 5 After Best Comedy Series Emmy Win|last1=McCarthy|first1=Tyler|last2=Castillo|first2=Monica|work=[[International Business Times]]|date=September 21, 2015|access-date=March 21, 2016|archive-date=March 24, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324074615/http://www.ibtimes.com/veep-creator-armando-iannucci-explains-why-hes-still-leaving-show-season-5-after-best-2106324|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="etiannucci">{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/news/166085_why_veep_creator_armando_iannucci_had_to_fire_himself/|title=Why 'Veep' Creator Armando Iannucci Had to Fire Himself|last=Lambe|first=Stacy|work=[[Entertainment Tonight]]|date=June 12, 2015|access-date=March 21, 2016|archive-date=March 23, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160323160611/http://www.etonline.com/news/166085_why_veep_creator_armando_iannucci_had_to_fire_himself/|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Filming===
[[Image:Calvert Street In Charles Village Baltimore.jpg|thumb|[[Charles Village, Baltimore]], one of the areas where ''Veep'' filmed for its first season production<ref name="patchcharles">{{cite web|url=http://patch.com/maryland/northbaltimore/tv-show-veep-films-in-charles-village|title=TV Show VEEP Films in Charles Village|last=Bednar|first=Adam|publisher=[[Patch.com|Patch]]|date=October 7, 2011|access-date=March 21, 2016|archive-date=March 23, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160323233115/http://patch.com/maryland/northbaltimore/tv-show-veep-films-in-charles-village|url-status=live}}</ref>]]
The pilot episode was filmed in February 2011 in [[Maryland]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2011/10/03/hbo-to-start-filming-veep-in-maryland-this-week/ |title=HBO To Start Filming VEEP In Maryland This Week |publisher=CBS Baltimore |date=October 3, 2011 |access-date=April 21, 2015 |archive-date=July 21, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721092746/http://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2011/10/03/hbo-to-start-filming-veep-in-maryland-this-week/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and filming for the series began in October 2011 in [[Baltimore]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/tv/z-on-tv-blog/bal-hbo-series-veep-starts-production-baltimore-20111003,0,1225743.story |title=HBO's series 'VEEP' starring Julia Louis-Dreyfus begins production in Maryland |work=The Baltimore Sun |first=David |last=Zurawik |date=October 3, 2011 |access-date=April 21, 2015 |archive-date=October 18, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111018064825/http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/tv/z-on-tv-blog/bal-hbo-series-veep-starts-production-baltimore-20111003,0,1225743.story |url-status=live }}</ref> after several months of rehearsal designed to get the actors comfortable improvising with one another.<ref>{{cite web |title=Episode 68: Featuring Sufe Bradshaw |url=http://www.rosscarey.com/2012/07/10/episode-68-featuring-sufe-bradshaw/ |publisher=RossCarey.com |date=July 10, 2012 |access-date=April 21, 2015 |archive-date=October 15, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131015094408/http://www.rosscarey.com/2012/07/10/episode-68-featuring-sufe-bradshaw/ |url-status=live }}</ref> For its first season, ''Veep'' reportedly hired 978 local Maryland residents, generating $40 million for the state, according to the Maryland Film Office.<ref name="marylandfilmoffice">{{cite web|url=http://www.bmoremedia.com/features/lizchudayacting021913.aspx|title=Break a leg: Baltimore actress Liz Chuday talks 'VEEP'|last=Dash|first=Julehka|publisher=Bmore Media|date=February 19, 2013|access-date=March 21, 2016|archive-date=March 24, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324040048/http://www.bmoremedia.com/features/lizchudayacting021913.aspx|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="baltimoremarylandfilmoffice">{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2013-05-01/entertainment/bal-hbo-renews-veep-for-third-season-20130501_1_armando-iannucci-vice-president-meyer-sufe-bradshaw|title=HBO renews Baltimore-made 'VEEP' for a third season|last=Zurawik|first=David|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|date=May 1, 2013|access-date=March 21, 2016|archive-date=March 24, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324014946/http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2013-05-01/entertainment/bal-hbo-renews-veep-for-third-season-20130501_1_armando-iannucci-vice-president-meyer-sufe-bradshaw|url-status=live}}</ref> Season 2 production began shooting in November 2012, continuing to film in [[Baltimore]] and other areas of [[Maryland]]. ''Veep'' primarily filmed on a [[sound stage]] constructed from a [[Columbia, Maryland]] industrial warehouse, where replicas of places such as the [[Eisenhower Executive Office Building]] and [[West Wing]] were also built.<ref name="louisdreyfusvulture">{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2013/12/julia-louis-dreyfus-talks-veep-enough-said.html|title=Julia Louis-Dreyfus in the Present Tense: How the Actress Made Her Transformational Turn on Veep|last=van Meter|first=Jonathan|work=[[Vulture (blog)|Vulture]]|date=December 8, 2013|access-date=March 21, 2016|archive-date=March 24, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324021414/http://www.vulture.com/2013/12/julia-louis-dreyfus-talks-veep-enough-said.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="usatodayveep">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2013/04/09/set-visit-hbo-veep/2059131/|title=From Baltimore, 'Veep' holds a mirror to D.C.|last=Blas|first=Lorena|work=[[USA Today]]|date=April 9, 2013|access-date=March 21, 2016|archive-date=March 30, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160330062746/http://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2013/04/09/set-visit-hbo-veep/2059131/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="wapostveep2013">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/julia-louis-dreyfus-savoring-veeps-wicked-sense-of-hubris/2013/04/11/2cabc33c-9e46-11e2-a2db-efc5298a95e1_story.html|title=Julia Louis-Dreyfus, savoring 'Veep's' wicked sense of hubris|last=Stuever|first=Hank|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=April 12, 2013|access-date=March 21, 2016|archive-date=March 15, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315100629/https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/julia-louis-dreyfus-savoring-veeps-wicked-sense-of-hubris/2013/04/11/2cabc33c-9e46-11e2-a2db-efc5298a95e1_story.html|url-status=live}}</ref> The show continued filming in Maryland for its third and fourth seasons, as a bill was approved by [[Maryland House of Delegates|state lawmakers]] in April 2013 that increased tax credits for film and TV productions in the state.<ref name="baltimoremarylandfilmoffice"/><ref name="marylandfilmbill2013">{{cite web|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/politics/blog/bal-assembly-approves-25-million-in-film-tax-credits-20130402-story.html|title=Assembly approves $25 million in film tax credits|last=Cox|first=Erin|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|date=April 2, 2013|access-date=March 21, 2016|archive-date=March 24, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324014554/http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/politics/blog/bal-assembly-approves-25-million-in-film-tax-credits-20130402-story.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="hborenewseasonfour">{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2014-04-22/entertainment/bal-hbo-renews-veep-for-a-fourth-season-20140421_1_sarandos-netflix-stock-media-rights-capital"|title=HBO to return to Baltimore for 'Veep' Season 4|last=Zurawik|first=David|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|date=April 22, 2014|access-date=March 21, 2016}}</ref> Later filming locations included [[Annapolis]] and the Physical Sciences Complex in the [[University of Maryland]], [[College Park, Maryland|College Park]] campus.<ref name="wmarcastcall">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc2news.com/entertainment/calling-all-actors-hbos-veep-casting-for-season-4-in-baltimore|title=Calling all actors: HBO's 'Veep' casting for season 4 in Baltimore|publisher=[[WMAR-TV|WMAR-TV (ABC)]]|date=July 24, 2014|access-date=March 21, 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324084036/http://www.abc2news.com/entertainment/calling-all-actors-hbos-veep-casting-for-season-4-in-baltimore|archive-date=March 24, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name="washingtonianveep">{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonian.com/2013/10/01/veep-is-filming-at-the-university-of-maryland-this-week/|last=Gilbert|first=Sophie|title=Veep Is Filming at the University of Maryland This Week|work=[[Washingtonian (magazine)|Washingtonian]]|date=October 1, 2013|access-date=March 21, 2016|archive-date=March 24, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324073156/http://www.washingtonian.com/2013/10/01/veep-is-filming-at-the-university-of-maryland-this-week/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="diamondbackveep">{{cite web|url=http://www.dbknews.com/archives/article_a972da76-316d-11e3-aa29-0019bb30f31a.html|title=HBO's Veep films scenes on campus|last=Blasey|first=Laura|work=[[The Diamondback]]|date=October 9, 2013|access-date=March 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024041812/http://www.dbknews.com/archives/article_a972da76-316d-11e3-aa29-0019bb30f31a.html|archive-date=October 24, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>

Principal photography moved from Baltimore to [[Los Angeles]] in the show's fifth season after being one of a few series to be awarded [[Movie production incentives in the United States#State-by-state|tax incentives]] from the [[California Film Commission]], as part of an expanded $330 million California Film Tax Credit program signed by [[Governor of California|Governor]] [[Jerry Brown]] in 2014.<ref name="veeplawapost">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/md-politics/hbo-veep-is-headed-west-moving-its-production-from-md-to-los-angeles/2015/06/18/36463e20-15fb-11e5-9518-f9e0a8959f32_story.html|title=HBO: 'Veep' is headed west, moving its production from Md. to Los Angeles|last=Wiggins|first=Ovetta|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=June 18, 2015|access-date=March 18, 2016|archive-date=August 4, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150804125028/http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/md-politics/hbo-veep-is-headed-west-moving-its-production-from-md-to-los-angeles/2015/06/18/36463e20-15fb-11e5-9518-f9e0a8959f32_story.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="veepcalivariety">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/artisans/news/californias-expanded-tax-credit-veep-american-horror-1201510491/|title=California's Expanded Tax Credit Set for 'Veep,' 'American Horror Story'|last=McNary|first=Dave|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=June 2, 2015|access-date=March 18, 2016|archive-date=March 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160321145139/http://variety.com/2015/artisans/news/californias-expanded-tax-credit-veep-american-horror-1201510491/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="deadlinecalitax">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/09/california-film-tv-tax-credit-bill-signed-jerry-brown-hollywood-836075/|title=Hooray For Hollywood! Gov. Brown Signs Film & TV Tax Credit Bill Extension|last=Patten|first=Dominic|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=September 18, 2014|access-date=March 18, 2016|archive-date=March 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304145419/http://deadline.com/2014/09/california-film-tv-tax-credit-bill-signed-jerry-brown-hollywood-836075/|url-status=live}}</ref> Filming took place for part of the show's fifth season in [[Washington, D.C.]], from February 25, 2016, to March 3, 2016. As a result of [[HBO]]'s Community Impact program, a select number of local D.C. residents also worked on the production during the eight-day film shoot in the area.<ref name="filmingdc">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/local/wp/2016/02/29/veep-is-filming-in-d-c-and-these-lucky-residents-are-helping-on-set/|title='Veep' is filming in D.C., and these lucky residents are helping on set|last=Stein|first=Perry|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=February 29, 2016|access-date=March 18, 2016|archive-date=March 9, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309100912/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/local/wp/2016/02/29/veep-is-filming-in-d-c-and-these-lucky-residents-are-helping-on-set/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="hbocommunityprogram">{{cite web|url=http://www.novacvideo.org/hbo/veep|title=HBO Community P.A. Training Program|publisher=New Orleans Video Access Center|access-date=March 18, 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320234318/http://www.novacvideo.org/hbo/veep|archive-date=March 20, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Areas in D.C. where production was reportedly found filming include the [[Superior Court of the District of Columbia|Superior Court]], the [[Spring Valley, Washington, D.C.|Spring Valley neighborhood]] (where Julia Louis-Dreyfus once lived), and [[Dupont Circle]]'s [[Kramerbooks & Afterwords|Kramerbooks]] [[independent bookstore]].<ref name="veepfilmingdc">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/reliable-source/wp/2016/03/01/veep-is-filming-in-washington-and-its-a-homecoming-for-julia-louis-dreyfus/|title='Veep' is filming in Washington, and it's a homecoming for Julia Louis-Dreyfus|last=Heil|first=Emily|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=March 1, 2016|access-date=March 18, 2016|archive-date=March 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304103714/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/reliable-source/wp/2016/03/01/veep-is-filming-in-washington-and-its-a-homecoming-for-julia-louis-dreyfus/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="veepkramerbooks">{{cite web|url=https://www.borderstan.com/2016/03/04/duponts-kramerbooks-may-appear-in-season-5-of-veep/|title=Dupont's Kramerbooks to Appear in Season 5 of "Veep"|last=Regan|first=Tim|publisher=Borderstan|date=March 4, 2016|access-date=March 18, 2016|archive-date=March 27, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160327142957/https://www.borderstan.com/2016/03/04/duponts-kramerbooks-may-appear-in-season-5-of-veep/|url-status=live}}</ref> The seventh and final season wrapped filming in December 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/12/19/veep-wraps-production-season-7/ |title=Veep stars say goodbye to show on emotional final day of shooting |work=Entertainment Weekly |first=Dan |last=Snierson |date=December 19, 2018 |access-date=December 22, 2018 |archive-date=December 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181222221456/https://ew.com/tv/2018/12/19/veep-wraps-production-season-7/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

